                            <h2>VentureCrowd CEO Steve Maarbani spoke to Ticker INVEST about a new tax incentive designed to generate investment into Australia’s medtech and biotech industries.
                            </h2>

                            <p>
                                <strong>
                                    Watch the recording of the interview below.</strong>
                            </p>
                            <div class="fluid-video-wrapper">
                                <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/yqmYuUtJHBo" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture"></iframe>
                            </div>
                            

                            <div class="post-body-rich-text text-left mt-5">

                                <h2>Short on time? Here's the summary:</h2>
                            </div>
                            <br/>
                            <ul class="p-rich_text_list p-rich_text_list__bullet" data-stringify-type="unordered-list" data-indent="0">
                                <li>
                                    In this week’s federal budget the government introduced a <a href="https://venturecrowd.file.force.com/sfc/dist/version/download/?oid=00D2v000000WjFp&ids=0682v00000JOMdp&d=%2Fa%2F2v000000EJpb%2F_Ctos.XI9JpZKOmJVw_6vNlq_eyfNF9ND86uGlzsVkc&asPdf=false" download="new tax incentive">new tax incentive</a> designed to generate investment into Australia’s medtech and biotech industries
                                </li>
                                <li> 
                                    Essentially, the program reduces the tax rate for income earned from new medical and biotech patents developed in Australia to 17% (around half the current tax rate for large corporates)                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    The purpose of the incentive is to encourage investment in research and development and encourage companies to develop and use Australian innovation.                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    Australia has a solid history of producing world-class biotech and medtech innovation, but often the tax regimes in other countries make it more attractive to move the innovation overseas once the hard work is done, which is not good for Australia and this policy is designed to address that issue.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    The scheme starts on 1 July 2022 and details of the incentive are being worked out in consultation with industry.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <b>
                                        The signal to the market here is that the government is prepared to forgo revenue to encourage more R&amp;D in biotech and medtech and the commercialisation of that research here in Australia, and we welcome that decision.
                                    </b>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    The message for investors is that medtech and biotech investment will become more lucrative and as a result we expect that over the next 12 months there will be more opportunities to invest in medical technology and biotechnology companies, so look out for those opportunities and invest early.
                                </li>
                            </ul>

                            

